descriptions: New website created (currently accessible through the EPFL network and in its development version), The official launch of the website will be mid-August and the link have been already registered under https://masonrydb.epfl.ch
Masonry Shake Table Database: Open database of shake table tests and numerical models of unreinforced masonry (URM) buildings
Web-based platform dedicated to shake table tests conducted on unreinforced masonry buildings
Web-based interfaces, visualization features and search capabilities developed by ENAC-IT4R
Open database of shake table tests and numerical models of URM buildings
The new website created comprises a database of experimental results from shake table tests conducted on unreinforced masonry buildings
The website also includes a database of ready-to-use numerical models
A database of shake-table tests conducted on unreinforced masonry buildings, containing experimental results and numerical models
Experimental data set containing shake-table accelerations and top displacement histories (44 files, 30 MB uncompressed)
A database of shake-table tests conducted on unreinforced masonry buildings
OpenSees model input files for dynamic analysis of a four-storey mixed URM-RC building; VTK code for geometry visualization by Jose Gallardo Briones
Python API and command line

Equivalent frame model (EFM) assumptions for multi-storey mixed URM-RC wall; macroelement for masonry by Vanin et al. (2019); Rayleigh damping proportional to mass and secant stiffness; rigid wall-to-wall and floor-to-wall connections
A training session is expected at the SAHC conference to be held at EPFL in September 2025, where a large number of researchers from around the world focused on masonry structures will be present
Paper submitted and accepted in the Journal Earthquake Spectra under the name “A database of shake-table tests conducted on unreinforced masonry buildings”
Manuscript (under progress) that makes use of the data provided in the platform for the quantification of uncertainties in the seismic assessment of unreinforced masonry buildings
Dynamic testing of a four-storey building with reinforced concrete and unreinforced masonry walls: blind prediction, test results and data set
Presentation of the database and web-based platform at the World Conference of Earthquake Engineering (WCEE) held in Milan in July 2024.
Presentation of the platform made in Colombia, Medellin. The event was organized as part of a project related to the seismic safety of rural schools in Colombia
Activity organized within the EESD lab for testing the platform

This number is based on statistics collected from the Zenodo repository at https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.11093882, given the total amount of views and downloads of the database already made. The community being benefited is mainly the research community working on unreinforced masonry buildings.

EXTRACTION STRATEGY:
  1. PRIMARY: Look for data in the specified location/table/section
  2. FALLBACK: If not found, search broader document context for semantically equivalent information
  3. FLEXIBILITY: Allow for format variations, OCR errors, and synonym usage

  LOCATION FLEXIBILITY:
  - Handle table format variations (column/row order, spacing, naming)
  - Consider synonyms and equivalent terms
  - Account for OCR/parsing errors that may affect document quality

  QUALITY STANDARDS:
  - Extract actual values found in the document
  - If uncertain, provide best interpretation with appropriate confidence
  - Only return null if the information category truly doesn't exist
  - Convert abbreviated amounts (k=1000) to full numbers where applicable
  

  REPORT OUTPUT FOCUS:
  - 15 standard output categories in "List of Outputs" table
  - Each category: quantity number, descriptions list, URLs list
  - Separate descriptions from URLs even when mixed in same cell
  - Academic collaborations vs Industrial partnerships (distinct categories)
  - Preserve all detailed descriptions and web addresses
